         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">21/11/68 ¶  ¶ This day, dear Mr Bentham, I have despatched the Grevilleas, a noble collection of about 2000 specimens, representing the  ¶ most charming ¶  of all the Australian Genera. Meissner &amp; RBr...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">68.11.21</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, ff. 353-4.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">21/11/68</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This day, dear Mr Bentham, I have despatched the Grevilleas, a noble collection of about 2000 specimens, representing the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">most charming</hi>
               </seg> of all the Australian Genera. Meissner &amp; RBrown<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. Brown (1810a).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> have left us little to describe; nor do I think that future researches in the interior will furnish many absolutely new species. You will make rapid progress with these plants after the great amount of labor, spent by me in their preliminary examination.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>M's 'preliminary examination’ of the <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name> was published in B68.12.01, pp 204-24, and continued in B68.12.02, pp 236-48.</p>
               </note> Much reduction must take place in the species. Indument, division or entirety of leaves &amp;c not giving always specific characters. Meissner places Grev. Huegelii &amp; G rigidissima widely apart,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See Meisner (1856), pp. 348-92: <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. rigidissima</seg> at p. 350, species 4, and <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. Heugelii</seg> at p. 372, species 92.</p>
               </note> altho they are but one species, and so it seems to be in other instances. Excellent as his work has generally been, it was never good as regards demarcation of species, and this is all the more remarkable when he had at Basel such fair opportunity of studying the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">variability</hi>
               </seg> of species in alpine regions. He evidently worked often also only with solitary specimens, and this must account for the great importance he attaches to characters, which larger collections now show to be trifling. I have often been able to complete the description of the fruits, and in one instance to show, that he matched wrong fruit specimens with the flowering ones. This refers to <name key="Grevillea%20Hookeriana">Grevillea Hookeriana</name>. In <name key="Banksia">Banksia</name> the very striking characters afforded in many instances by the seeds &amp; septa are previously quite negelected. That the dissepiment is formed by the testa I cannot see. The seed of a <name key="Banksia">Banksia</name> is very similar to that of a <name key="Hakea">Hakea</name>. The free wing in both genera is a continuation of the ordinary testa. I hope to send off before the end of the year the whole rest of the <name key="Proteaceae">Proteaceae</name> &amp; the <name key="Thymeleae">Thymeleae</name> also, which then gives you the whole of the <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name>, as already the following consignments have been made:</p>
